{
  "doc_id": "43770",
  "text": "Generation of carbonate-resistant lysosome/phagosome complexes must be performed in two steps because when Ca 2ϩ is present from the beginning of the reaction even docking is blocked (Figure 3 ). In this context it is interesting to note that Ca 2ϩ has been shown to disrupt the ability of IQGAP1 to cross-link F-actin [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , suggesting that IQGAP2 might have been responsible for mediating the differential Ca 2ϩ effects during our in vitro reactions. In vitro, the half-maximal Ca 2ϩ concentration required for acquisition of carbonate resistance lies between 1 and 10 M (Figure 3) , which is similar to results obtained for Ca 2ϩ -mediated fusion events in vivo [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] and during late endosome/lysosome fusion and yeast vacuole fusion in vitro [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . In previous studies the Ca 2ϩ dependence during endosome fusion assays was found to be bellshaped [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] , whereas Ca 2ϩ -induced consolidation in our scintillation proximity assay is sigmoidal (Figure 3 ). If our current results extend to other systems and Ca 2ϩ blocks tethering while promoting the fusion of vesicles that have already docked, optimal Ca 2ϩ concentrations in single-step fusion reactions might potentially reflect a synthesis between least inhibition and maximal consolidation.",
